AIM to buy things in cash and avoid taking them on credit. That is a stern warning from Lillian Gatjen, a credit adviser for Debt Solutions in the Joburg CBD. “Bad debt is a slippery slope that should be avoided at all costs, and the simple message here is that you must avoid the temptation to want to have everything now. Save for what you want,” she said. Gatjen said she deals with overindebted clients every day, helping them through debt counselling to recover from bad debt. “A debt consolidation programme helps to remove people from the debt trap through consolidation of all their debt into one affordable monthly instalment,” she said. But not all debt is bad debt, according to TransUnion director Garnet Jensen. “The bottom line is that in 2021 precious few of us can afford to pay cash for a home, car, tertiary education or even furniture. In fact, having credit is practically essential to navigating modern lifestyles,” said Jensen. She said the trick is to know the difference between good debt and bad debt, and managing your credit wisely. SunMoney asked Jensen what to watch out for: